# Rust Conventions for sfdoc

## Error Handling
- Use `anyhow::Result` in `main.rs` and all binary-facing code (top-level orchestration)
- Use `thiserror` for structured errors in `error.rs` that may need to be matched on
- Use `.context("...")` / `.with_context(|| ...)` to add actionable messages at every `?`
- Never `.unwrap()` in production paths — only in tests or `OnceLock` initializers

## Async
- All Gemini API calls are `async` — use `tokio::spawn` for concurrent class processing
- Rate limiting via `tokio::sync::Semaphore` — acquire permit before each API call
- The top-level runtime is `#[tokio::main]` in `main.rs`

## Regex
- Compile each regex exactly once using `std::sync::OnceLock<Regex>` in a helper function
- Never compile a `Regex` inside a hot loop

## Naming
- Types: `PascalCase` — `ClassMetadata`, `ApexFile`, `GeminiClient`
- Functions/methods: `snake_case`
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Test modules: `#[cfg(test)] mod tests { ... }` at the bottom of each file

## Testing
- Unit tests live in the same file as the code they test (`#[cfg(test)] mod tests`)
- Use `tempfile::TempDir` for filesystem tests (already a dev-dependency)
- Test the public API surface; avoid testing private regex internals directly
- Integration tests (if added) go in `tests/`

## Dependencies
| Crate | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| `clap` (derive) | CLI parsing |
| `tokio` (full) | Async runtime |
| `reqwest` (json) | HTTP client for Gemini |
| `serde` / `serde_json` | JSON serialization |
| `walkdir` | Directory traversal |
| `indicatif` | Progress bars |
| `anyhow` | Ergonomic errors (application layer) |
| `thiserror` | Typed errors (library layer) |
| `regex` | Apex structural parsing |
| `tempfile` (dev) | Temp dirs in tests |

## Style
- Prefer `collect::<Result<Vec<_>>>()` over manual loops with `?`
- Use `OnceLock` not `lazy_static` — it is in `std` since Rust 1.70
- Keep `src/types.rs` as the single source of truth for shared structs
- Each module's public API should be minimal — re-export only what `main.rs` needs
